  "text": "Among SP_PIR_Keywords (Additional file S1), unique responses were the high impact and activation during lactation of the terms: 'Molibdenum', whose importance is supported by the fact that it has been found to be the most transferred microelement in human milk [CITATION_1] ; 'Antimicrobial' likely related to the increased expression of several proteins related to the innate immune system (e.g., osteopontin, XDH [CITATION_2] ); 'Growth arrest' supporting the above conclusion that the regulation of cell growth is actively under transcriptomics control in mammary; and 'Protein synthesis inhibitor', which suggested that the decrease in protein synthesis machinery during lactation is an important and tightly regulated phenomena as also discussed above and in a previous work [CITATION_3] .",
